"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44085"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41691"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy is being review by the paediatrics team as an in-patient following a seizure six hours ago. The seizure was described as a tonic-clonic seizure that lasted approximately two minutes. He was incontinent of urine and was post-ictal for 40 minutes afterwards. The seizure was witnessed by his mother. He has never had a seizure previously and there is no family history of seizures according to the mother.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination revealed that he is afebrile, and all other vital signs are within normal range. His heart sounds are dual and his chest clear. He has seven small hypo-pigmented lesions across his body and an erythematous rash across his cheeks comprised of small red nodules. Initial blood tests are normal, and he is awaiting a brain MRI scan and an EEG.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this boy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neurofibromatosis type 1","Neurofibromatosis type 2","Hydrocephalus","Pilocytic astrocytoma","Tuberous sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case is an example of a seizure in an afebrile child. There can be many causes of this that need to be further explored and ruled out. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpace occupying lesions such as tumours can cause seizures with the most common brain tumour in children being a \u003Cstrong\u003Epilocytic astrocytoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Hence, this could explain his presentation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, the presence of a seizure along with hypo-pigmented spots and a facial rash suggests a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberous sclerosis. \u003C/strong\u003ETuberous sclerosis is a genetic condition affecting a range of organ systems through abnormalities in cell differentiation and proliferation that cause hamartomas. Spontaneous genetic mutations occur in 65% of the cases, so the family history is not always indicative. The common organs affected are skin, brain, eye, kidney and heart. Therefore, common presentations of the condition include skin lesions, seizures and developmental delay. Some of skin lesions of tuberous sclerosis are described in the case such as hypomelanotic macules (hypo-pigmented patches of skin, also known as ash-leaf spots) and facial angiofibroma (red rash across the cheeks in a butterfly distribution comprised of small red rodules. Therefore, the presentation of seizure along with the distinct skin lesions suggests a diagnosis of tuberous sclerosis is the most likely out of these options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocephalus \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a cause of seizures in children. There is an abnormal build up of cerebral spinal fluid in the ventricles within the brain. This can cause increased intraventricular pressure and precipitate seizures. This child does not display symptoms of raised intracranial pressure (headaches, vomiting, vision problems) or signs of hydrocephalus (increased head circumference). There are also no skin signs that are specific to hydrocephalus, such as those described in this case. It can be treated by placing a surgical shunt to drain the fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurofibromatosis is also a genetic disorder that affects bone, soft tissue, skin and nervous system. \u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromatosis type 1\u003C/strong\u003E (NFT1) has features of 6 or more caf\u00e9-au-lait macules (light brown skin macules), freckling in skin folds, lisch nodules in the iris and neurofibromas (benign nerve tumour that forms soft bumps on/under the skin). This patient has hypo-pigmented skin lesions rather than pigmented caf\u00e9-au-lait macules and there is no mention of skin neurofibromas present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromatosis type 2\u003C/strong\u003E (NFT2) is characterised by multiple tumours/neurofibromas of the brain and spinal cord. It does not have skin signs such as NFT1, but often presents with hearing loss due to bilateral acoustic neuromas. There is no mention of impaired hearing in the stem. Both NFT1 and NFT2 can present with seizures due to the presence of tumours in the brain. But, with the presence of other physical signs suggestive of tuberous sclerosis, it makes NF a less likely cause in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tuberous sclerosis is a genetic condition that commonly affects the skin, brain, eye, kidneys and heart.","Neurofibromatosis type 1 has cafe-au-lait spots and skin neurofibromas, where as neurofibromatosis type 2 may present with bilateral acoustic neuromas (hearing loss) without skin signs","An afebrile seizure in a child requires a work-up for the cause"],"references":["Ngan V. Tuberous sclerosis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2003. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/tuberous-sclerosis/.","Bornhorst M, Frappaz D, Packer RJ. Pilocytic astrocytomas. Handb Clin Neurol. 2016;134:329-44. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26948364/","Ngan V. Neurofibromatosis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2003. Access at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/neurofibromatosis/.","St Louis EK, Cascino GD. Diagnosis of Epilepsy and Related Episodic Disorders. Continuum (Minneap Minn). 2016;22(1 Epilepsy):15-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26844728/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-21T20:59:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-21T20:59:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41691"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attri